We keep a few Nigerian Dwarf goats around for weed cleanup and entertainment value. They share their pen with a horde of barn cats who seem fascinated with the goats. When I feed in the mornings nobody seems to care who they are sharing their breakfast with. Cats will eat goat feed, goats will eat cat food. It usually takes me a few minutes to get each species to their assigned feed station, herding cats ain't easy. After I leave, they are on their own. Right now we have two wethers and one doe. When the males were young, I banded them to keep the population in check.

posts.author: Navasot
posts.text: lol im not full breed goat guy but a small hardy goat for a pet would either be Nubian if you dont got many neighbors or mainly a Spanish goat... Spanish will prolly be the best hardy goat in a small acre setting... The nubian has a bonus of getting milk from them since they are a dairy breed but they are also pretty noisey goats... more than normal and may tick some neighbors off... if you want some with value boer would be the best choice... but they eat alot and they get big for the most part... with any you will need to learn how to trim their feet and give wormer about every 3-4 weeks for it to be ideal... the spanish goat would most likely be the one you could tend to the least but still all goats like a dry climate and in a yard setting your going to see the grass get down low which makes it easy for them to get were the worms like to live and once they get worms they usually kill over.

posts.title: Salaries soar in the education, catering and retail sectors
posts.text:
search: Salaries soar in the education, catering and retail sectors 
The latest job market data from CV-Library reveals that salaries across the UK saw a steady increase of 1.3 per cent last month. 
As the year draws to a close, there is still a great deal of uncertainty surrounding the future of the UK economy. That said, the most recent job market data from CV-Library reveals salaries across the UK saw a steady increase of 1.3 per cent last month, when compared with data from October 2017. 
The statistics also show that the nation witnessed a year-on-year increase in salaries, rising by 1.9 per cent in November. What’s more, many key industries across the UK experienced stand-out growth which not only outpaced the national average, but also inflation. The sectors to see the highest increases in salaries last month include: 
Education – 7.7 per cent Legal – 5.6 per cent Recruitment – 1.7 per cent 
Not only this, but some of the nation’s key cities also saw a hike in advertised salaries in November. These included Cardiff (15.5 per cent), Brighton (7.4 per cent), Newcastle (5.4 per cent), Sheffield (4.1 per cent) and Glasgow (3.9 per ceny). 
Lee Biggins, founder and managing director of CV-Library comments, ‘It’s positive to see that salaries are on the rise across the UK, especially in some of the nation’s key cities and industries. With Christmas fast approaching many businesses will have been working hard to recruit for additional seasonal staff. Not only this, but in the run up to the New Year many organisations will be looking to boost their recruitment efforts ahead of the January rush.’ 
The data also reveals job vacancies saw a 5.8 per cent increase across the nation, when compared with data from the same period in 2016. What’s more, some of the key industries to witness a rise in salaries also experienced year-on-year job growth in November, with education, recruitment and retail increasing by 16.1 per cent, 11.1 per cent and 5.6 per cent respectively. 
Job applications across the UK decreased in November, falling by 6.4 per cent month-on-month. Though this may spark concerns for employers with live vacancies, it is not unusual for this time of year, as many candidates sit tight until Christmas is over with. We expect to see application rates pick back up in January, in keeping with the traditional New Year recruitment rush. 
Biggins concludes, ‘As we approach the New Year, we expect to see a certain amount of job growth, as businesses across the nation gear up for the January recruitment rush. That said, this year-on-year increase in job vacancies, and a fall in applications, could indicate that the skills gap is continuing to widen. 
‘November saw the announcement of the Autumn Budget, which offered some reassurance to the nation’s workers and businesses. New government partnerships aim to deliver training schemes across some of our key industries, to equip professionals with the skills they need and to begin bridging the gap. Investment in areas of education, particularly in science, technology, engineering, and maths (STEM) skills will hopefully begin to build a pipeline of talent for the future.’

posts.author: dkershen
posts.text:
I've got one Nigerian Dwarf, one Pygmy and one cross-bred between the two. If you want them to be pets and interact with people you need to get them very young and bottle feed them a while. One acre is a little small, but would support 2 goats if it has trees and underbrush for browse. Being herd animals they dont do good by themselves so suggest at least two. Small goats need very little feed if you have browse. Couple of negatives.. coyotes and bobcats love young goats. Goats love ornamental shrubs and flowers and will strip your landscaping clean. Male goats are susceptible to bladder stones, which can kill them, if they get into the wrong type of feed. Suggest ONLY feeding quality goat chow.
This is Oreo.
And this is Henry.

Originally Posted by Casinomeister Hi all,
It's no secret, but in case you have heard it mentioned - yes, the forum is getting ready for a make-over.
We have been testing newer - more robust software on a test site and we are almost ready for the export/import phase. This will probably be happening early next week sometime.
The software is amazing. Those who use your phones to access the site will be thanking me. The mobile version is awesome. And the desk top version is fast - it has pretty much the same look and feel, and it is more responsive. The CAG members have been checking it out for a little over a week, and so far no one has mutinied .
Anyway - some caveats:
The "Thanks". We are having problems importing the thanking system. The new forum has a thanks system in place, but does not display the older ones in the forum posts. So we may have to ditch that and start afresh.
There are newer "Thanks" plugins for the new forum, it just won't be able to calculate the ones you have already been given. It has imported the likes, so you will have those to admire.
Social Groups or the Meister Clubs: We may have to ditch these as well. The software is just not importing these correctly. We can keep a copy of them and perhaps import them at a later date, but not that many people are using them, and this doesn't justify holding off on the relaunch. Sorry for those of you who have been using the Meister Clubs.
Blogs : These aren't porting over very well either. So they will have to be loaded up at a latter time. Perhaps it could be done on the Word Press sections. We will see.
Who has read a thread: This works fine, but it hasn't imported the historical "reads". Sorry 'bout that.
When the export/import of the forum commences, it is going to take some time (it takes 5 hours for the PMs alone), so the forum will be down, but in a "read only" mode. You will be able to peruse the posts/threads etc.; you just won't be able to do anything that will change the data base.
So watch this space for more info. I'm trying to create a new thread in the "Mesiter Minions" for withdrawal reports - but I can't create a thread. Is this classified as Mesiter club, hence why it doesn't work? I just don't see a button to create a new thread any more!
Thanks!

        func_search_dir proc
            push 0          
            call SetLastError
            push offset fData
            push offset fDir
            call FindFirstFile

            mov hFile, eax
            
            push offset fData
            push hFile
            call FindNextFile

            next:                       ; loop until no more files left in the folder
                push offset fData
                push hFile
                call FindNextFile

                cmp eax, 0
                je end_f                     

                cmp [fData].dwFileAttributes, FILE_ATTRIBUTE_DIRECTORY
                je directory_found
                
                jmp next

                directory_found:
                    push [hFile]

                    push offset [fData].cFileName
                    call SetCurrentDirectory

                    call func_search_dir

                    push offset prev_dir
                    call SetCurrentDirectory

                    pop eax

                    mov hFile, eax

                    jmp next

posts.author: Stefan Adams
posts.title: Miami Hurricanes Recruiting Radar: Top247 Postseason Update
posts.text: Rec 247 Sports To be clear, this article is in reference to 247Sports’ own site rankings, the Top247, NOT the 247Composite, in which all 4 major recruiting site’s rankings are taken into account and combined together. A day after Rivals updated their rankings, 247 Sports followed suit and did the same, releasing the newest version of the Top247 . As of today, Miami has the #3 class nationally and that is reflected in this list, as Storm18 has 12 commits that made the new Top247, the same number that were included in the previous update. Some of the names have changed, though. Miami switched out Artur Sitkowski for Mark Richt’s newest QB protege, Jarren Williams . The Peach State product committed to Miami today over Ohio State . CB DJ Ivey made a huge move onto the Top247 after spending the entire cycle outside of the ranking. The newly minted 4-star has long been the most underrated part of Miami’s class and Ivey is taking the first step in living up to those Artie Burns comparisons. Others making big leaps were American Heritage DT Nesta Silvera , who racked up 12 sacks for a team playing for the state title, and TE Brevin Jordan , who caught 57 passes for 1,025 yards and 12 touchdowns for perennial West Coast powerhouse Bishop Gorman. Jordan is now the 105th best player in the nation and #4 TE, while Silvera shot up 59 spots to #184 overall. A few UM commits that had notable slides within the ranking were DB Al Blades Jr. and WR Brian Hightower . Blades had a limited role this season in a loaded St. Thomas defensive backfield, while Hightower got inconsistent QB play after IMG switched signal-callers throughout the season. Cleveland Reed fell out of the rankings altogether while also dropping to a 3-star (however, he still retains his 4th star in the 247Composite). Reed missed his senior season at Fort Meade with a knee injury, but is expected to be healthy for the 2018 campaign and plans to enroll in Miami early for spring ball. Below you can find a handy little chart of all the changes, up and down, of Miami commits within the newest Top247. Top247 Postseason Rankings Update
